      "id":"lifeandstyle/shortcuts/2013/oct/06/sex-box-participants-reveal-channel-4",
      "sectionId":"lifeandstyle",
      "sectionName":"Life and style",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-06T17:00:00Z",
      "webTitle":"Sex Box: the participants reveal what actually happened",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/shortcuts/2013/oct/06/sex-box-participants-reveal-channel-4",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/lifeandstyle/shortcuts/2013/oct/06/sex-box-participants-reveal-channel-4",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"2",
        "trailText":"<p>The Channel 4 show claims it will help Britain get over its sexual repression. But did actually having sex in the studio help people articulate their feelings about it?</p>",
        "headline":"Sex Box: the participants reveal what actually happened",
        "body":"<p>What makes six apparently sensible people agree to have sex in a box on national television? That is what Dean and Rachel, Matt and John, and Lynette and Des have done, in order to help Channel 4 <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2013/sep/23/sex-box-tv-show-reclaim-sex-pornography\" title=\"\">reclaim sex from pornography</a>, the stated aim of its Campaign for Real Sex Season.</p><p>\"We had just got back from holiday,\" says Dean, 21, a supermarket delivery driver. \"We were shopping in Reading. A guy came up to us and said, 'You look like a happy couple. We're doing this programme based on couples and their sex lives ...' I guess because we were in holiday mode, we gave him the time of day.\" Matt has a similar story: he and John were on holiday in Manchester (to coincide with Pride) when they were approached. \"We said yes there and then,\" says Matt, although many subsequent phone calls, Skype conversations and face-to-face meetings with producers ensued.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.channel4.com/programmes/sex-box\" title=\"\">Sex Box</a> seems to promise so much – the theory being that  people will talk more frankly about sex straight after having it – but putting sex into a box hardly fits with the anti-repression mission statement. If sex needs to be out in the open more, what is it doing in a shed in the middle of a television studio, with flashing blue lasers around it to indicate that something <em>exciting</em> is happening within?</p><p>Host Mariella Frostrup calls it \"a unique space\", which makes it sound a bit like a pop-up gallery – here for one 60-minute show only. Perhaps that is why time is on the mind of the participants. Off-camera,  they were told to spend around 30 minutes inside. Dean says he got around the problem of not over-running \"by taking my phone in with me\". It's not everyone's idea of a good time but his first act in the box was to \"set the timer\" on his phone.</p><p>Was there a bed? A rug?  Cushions? Dean says that his  contract prevents him from  describing the box's interior.  All he can say is that \"they tried to make it feel as homely as  possible – like a hotel room\". There were washing facilities, condoms and tissues, an emergency switch, but no  ensuite shower. Matt concurs. \"It was very basic.\"</p><p>For Matt and John, there were other technical hitches. It turns out the box has another door not visible to studio or TV audience. \"The funny thing is, you see us going into the box,\" says John. \"Then, because of union rules, everyone can only work so many hours without a break. So we came straight out the back door and went to our dressing room. We were able to go for a shower and everything, and at least start some foreplay before going back in.\"</p><p>Putting people in a box to have sex, and then asking them to wait until the crew has had its tea, sums up all that is wrong with this show. What did any of the participants think they were going to achieve?</p><p>John and Matt are both chefs,  and John didn't come out until 2007, in his mid-30s, \"because I lived at work\". He felt he had no choice but to be honest with his colleagues. He and Matt live together but, says John, \"Our private life isn't exactly private. You can't really do anything. You can't have anything delivered without them knowing – oh, another parcel for the gay couple upstairs. We were hoping to put a few facts right, that not all gay men wear dresses.\" Matt's reasons are similar. \"We're both gay but we're not really in a gay community as such. We don't have loads of gay friends. We thought just by being part of the conversation , we're doing our bit to show what it's like.\"</p><p>Unfortunately, the actual show's post-sex conversations make post-match interviews with football managers seem exciting. (It's a pity they couldn't have got Roy Hodgson on to liven things up.) When Dean is asked the big question – what did he and Rachel do in the box – he seems embarrassed. \"Main thing first, taking the clothes off obviously. Then,\" he tells the panel, \"just a bit of foreplay.\" Rachel nods. \"Then straight into it.\" Into what? \"Into sexual intercourse, obviously,\" says Dean. None of the participants in the final programme is articulate about their box sex. Speaking on the phone, John is more eloquent. He says that his and Matt's experience was \"like when me and Matt did anal for the first time. We hyped it up so much. It was so much better after, when it just happened without being planned and nature took its course.\"</p><p>There is a lesson for everyone there. Pornography can sleep  easy tonight.</p><p><em>Sex Box, Monday 7 October, 10pm, Channel 4</em></p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/419078562|2013-10-07T10:05:55Z|06d8c087afc98c51d7b89c00d852b0d07344f034 -->",
