        "body":"<p><strong>My partner and I have begun experimenting with sadomasochism. I was reluctant but she really wanted to explore it. I was surprised that not only was I good at it, but that I took great pleasure in hurting her. This is a woman I'm madly in love with. I've always been a kind, gentle man so I'm disturbed that I so enjoy physically hurting another human being</strong>.</p><p></p><p>In BDSM,  you must understand the notion of consensuality. If your partner&nbsp;gives you permission to inflict pain in an erotic context, the exact style&nbsp;and degree of that is agreed (understanding that the contract could be renegotiated at any time), and if&nbsp;you use appropriate safety mechanisms such as a \"safe word\", it is&nbsp;generally considered that consensuality is in place. But consent is brought into question when one has experienced physical, verbal or sexual trauma in the past, if you play under the influence of drugs or alcohol, if either has mental illness, or if permanent damage is likely to be caused. Consent is not just for the submissive person: you are conflicted about your dominant role, which in itself brings your consent into question. Think more carefully about your own limits. Define and express what is and isn't comfortable for you. And beware: dominant partners often experience burnout. Adjust your level of play accordingly.</p><p><em>• Pamela Stephenson Connolly is a psychotherapist who specialises in treating sexual disorders</em></p><p><em>• If you would like advice from Pamela Stephenson Connolly on sexual matters, send us a brief description of your concerns to </em><a href=\"mailto:private.lives@guardian.co.uk\" title=\"\"><em>private.lives@guardian.co.uk</em></a><em> (please don't send attachments).</em></p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/419072109|2013-10-07T10:05:55Z|22deec572929f6c9e24703923039110cd67b8989 -->",
